            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>“To the very strong and very glorious triumpher Princes Valentinian, very victorious master, and his brother Valens, our master ... maximus and Gratian ... our master Valens’s nephew, always Augusti, Domitius Modestus, of clarissimus rank (?), praetorian prefect and ... of clarissimus rank, comes and magister devoted to their divine spirit and majesty ... disposing ... decemprimus appointed ... of the ballistae makers through ... removed the perfectissimus patron and ...”</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="fr">
                <p>“...”</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <p>“Ai Principi trionfatori fortissimi e gloriosissimi Valentiniano signore vittoriosissimo e suo fratello Valente, nostro signore ... massimo e Graziano ... nostro signore nipote di Valente sempre Augusti, Domitius Modestus, chiarissimo (?), prefetto del pretorio e ... chiarissimo, <foreign>comes</foreign> e <foreign>magister</foreign>, devoti al nume e alla maestà loro ... disponendo ... decemprimo preposto ... dei costruttori di balliste per ... ha rimosso il patrono perfettissimo e ...”</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Domitius Modestus was praetorian prefect of Oriens from 369 to 377 AD under the emperor Valens. On his career cfr. Vogler 1992, pp. 450, 453-454, 458-460.
                The inscription is a dedication made by Modestus to all the emperors, both of the Eastern and the Western part of the empire, that is Valens in the East and Valentinian I in the West together with his son Gratian.</p>
            </div>
